perf: migrate inline base64 images to Supabase Storage + button fixes

Root cause of slow load + non-working buttons: legacy CMS rows stored
image bytes inline as base64 data URLs. Home page payload was 45 MB
of HTML so React could not finish hydrating before the user gave up,
meaning click handlers never attached and buttons appeared dead.

After running the migration:
  Home page payload   45 MB  -> 167 KB   (273x smaller)
  Cold load           10-45s -> 1.2s
  Warm load           6-10s  -> 0.3s

Changes:
- scripts/migrate-base64-to-storage.mjs: one-time idempotent script
  that scans every image column across 16 tables, decodes any data:
  URL, uploads to the right Supabase Storage bucket (images, documents,
  resumes, gallery) and updates the row with the public URL. Ran
  against production: 13 images migrated, 0 failures.

- components/public/HomePageClient.tsx, app/(public)/portfolio/page.tsx:
  Removed absolute-positioned <Link> overlay that wrapped action <a>
  children. Anchor-inside-anchor was invalid HTML, breaking hydration
  and event handlers. Restored the original Vite pattern (no card-wide
  navigation overlay) and added an inline "View Project" link in the
  card body.

- app/layout.tsx: added suppressHydrationWarning to <html> and <body>
  for browser extensions (Grammarly, crypto wallets) that mutate body
  attributes before React mounts. Added data-scroll-behavior="smooth"
  to silence the Next.js dev warning.

- app/(public)/layout.tsx: removed duplicate <AuroraMesh /> (root
  layout already renders it once).

- README.md: rewritten for Next.js (was still describing the old
  Vite stack).

- .gitignore: exclude .serena/ entirely (editor cache, not project).
